{"term":"1973","caseName":"Central Tablet Mfg. Company v. United States","caseLink":"https://www.oyez.org/cases/1973/73-593","caseTranscripts":[{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 25, 1974","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/15889","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We’ll hear arguments next in 73-593, Central Tablet Manufacturing against the United States.","start":0,"stop":24.027,"duration":24.03},{"text":"Mr. Snyder, you may proceed whenever you’re ready.","start":24.027,"stop":26.947,"duration":2.92}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":26.947,"stop":31.115,"duration":4.17},{"text":"Central Tablet Manufacturing Company versus the United States is an income tax case arising under Section 337 of the Internal Revenue Code.","start":31.115,"stop":43.009,"duration":11.89},{"text":"Section 337 provides in substance that sales or exchanges by a corporation within a 12-month period following adoption of a plan of liquidation shall be free from tax to the corporation provided that during the same 12-month period, all of the assets of the corporation are conveyed or transferred to stockholders in liquidation of the corporation.","start":43.009,"stop":74.23,"duration":31.22},{"text":"Section 337 is a remedial statute enacted in 1954 to eliminate the need for determining in the course of a corporate liquidation whether assets are sold by the corporation or whether instead, they are sold to stockholders following distribution of the assets to the shareholders.","start":74.23,"stop":101.278,"duration":27.05},{"text":"By eliminating this determination, the statue eliminates the tax on both the corporation and the stockholders with the same sale or exchange transaction.","start":101.278,"stop":117.574,"duration":16.3},{"text":"In the series of lower court decision’s following the enactment of 337, it was held that involuntary conversions by a casualty ought to be included within the term sales or exchanges as used in Section 337.","start":117.574,"stop":137.008,"duration":19.43},{"text":"These decisions were subsequently acquiesced in by the Internal Revenue Service.","start":137.008,"stop":143.698,"duration":6.69},{"text":"The new question presented here by Central Tablet is whether in the application of Section 337 to involuntary conversions by a casualty, the involuntary conversion occurs at the time of the casualty, which in this case Central Tablet preceded adoption of a plan of liquidation or whether it occurs on the right to insurance proceeds arises which under the facts of Central Tablet occurred after adoption of the plan of liquidation.","start":143.698,"stop":183.096,"duration":39.4},{"text":"Briefly stated --","start":183.096,"stop":184.514,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Let me see if I understand that.","start":184.514,"stop":186.691,"duration":2.18},{"text":"I thought that liability was accepted here.","start":186.691,"stop":190.833,"duration":4.14}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, liability was neither accepted nor rejected, Your Honor.","start":190.833,"stop":194.603,"duration":3.77},{"text":"I think in response to your question in trying to state it fairly, I think the very fact that we negotiate these insurance claims was a recognition tacitly on the part of the insurance carriers that there was some liability, but they neither admitted nor disallowed liability.","start":194.603,"stop":216.107,"duration":21.5},{"text":"They did however reject our proofs of loss in the case.","start":216.107,"stop":222.161,"duration":6.05}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"But everything about on which their liability depended, it already occurred?","start":222.161,"stop":227.418,"duration":5.26}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don’t know.","start":227.418,"stop":228.958,"duration":1.54},{"text":"The fire had occurred, of course.","start":228.958,"stop":230.604,"duration":1.65}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, and then the -- then the --","start":230.604,"stop":233.471,"duration":2.87}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Proofs of loss?","start":233.471,"stop":233.843,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Policy -- the policy had been issued and--","start":233.843,"stop":237.135,"duration":3.29}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"The policy had been issued, the proof of losses have been rejected.","start":237.135,"stop":241.224,"duration":4.09},{"text":"Now certainly, this is a condition --","start":241.224,"stop":243.242,"duration":2.02}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand.","start":243.242,"stop":243.614,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"To recovery under the policy.","start":243.614,"stop":244.676,"duration":1.06}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"But from then on, it was -- if there were arguments that was arguments over the facts that had already occurred, or the meaning of instruments already issued?","start":244.676,"stop":255.614,"duration":10.94}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think that’s correct.","start":255.614,"stop":258.534,"duration":2.92},{"text":"There's also a challenge to the validity of the policies but we briefly state all of the facts that I think are necessary for the Court to understand, the factual background of Central Tablet.","start":258.534,"stop":272.234,"duration":13.7}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Incidentically, what's the basis of the property -- the adjusted base is very low here.","start":272.234,"stop":277.862,"duration":5.63}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it was an old company, the building --","start":277.862,"stop":280.092,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Was it zero, as a matter of fact?","start":280.092,"stop":281.632,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"No, it’s not --","start":281.632,"stop":282.057,"duration":0.43}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"It was not, so that is the amount of the insurance proceeds then in bore on whether there would be a gain or a loss, I take it.","start":282.057,"stop":289.066,"duration":7.01}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":289.066,"stop":291.137,"duration":2.07}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Was there ever any question as to the amount so that the loss could have resolved?","start":291.137,"stop":302.553,"duration":11.42}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t believe so, no.","start":302.553,"stop":304.04,"duration":1.49},{"text":"I don’t know.","start":304.04,"stop":306.429,"duration":2.39},{"text":"Frankly, I don’t recall the figures.","start":306.429,"stop":308.978,"duration":2.55},{"text":"The biggest dispute with regard to the building policy was whether or not a coinsurance clause applied.","start":308.978,"stop":316.093,"duration":7.12},{"text":"The insurers took the position that it, did had it applied or if it did apply, it reduced the limit of coverage approximately 40%.","start":316.093,"stop":327.244,"duration":11.15},{"text":"Now this, like every other factual issue that we got into and of course the negotiations was never determined.","start":327.244,"stop":335.952,"duration":8.71},{"text":"What finally happened is we started to talk in terms of numbers and agreed on a dollar amount.","start":335.952,"stop":342.908,"duration":6.96},{"text":"But in addition to this, of course there was the usual question of the value of the building at the time of the loss, with regard to the personal property that was a question of a value of the property.","start":342.908,"stop":355.28,"duration":12.37},{"text":"Of course, at the time of the loss, there was a question of whether some of the personal property was repairable.","start":355.28,"stop":361.439,"duration":6.16},{"text":"There was even a question with regard with part of the machinery and equipment, whether the damage to it had been caused by the fire and the water that had been used to put out the fire, or whether instead it had been caused by the elements and the failure of the insurer to properly take care of that equipment after the fire.","start":361.439,"stop":382.307,"duration":20.87},{"text":"This was not a great bone of contention.","start":382.307,"stop":385.227,"duration":2.92},{"text":"And I don’t -- I can’t tell you how many percentage-wise the number of machines it involved, but it was a question.","start":385.227,"stop":393.511,"duration":8.28},{"text":"Here again, it was never sudden.","start":393.511,"stop":395.21,"duration":1.7},{"text":"It was never decided that the insurer was or was not at fault.","start":395.21,"stop":399.352,"duration":4.14},{"text":"We finally agreed on numbers and on dollars.","start":399.352,"stop":403.175,"duration":3.82},{"text":"The negotiations of these claims took some two years.","start":403.175,"stop":408.75,"duration":5.57},{"text":"The building claim took approximately nine months to reach a settlement.","start":408.75,"stop":415.016,"duration":6.27},{"text":"Settlement was after adoption of the plan of liquidation.","start":415.016,"stop":419.795,"duration":4.78},{"text":"The personal property tax claims were settled approximately a year after the fire.","start":419.795,"stop":426.804,"duration":7.01},{"text":"The business interruption loss claim, which is not here in contention, was two years after the fire before it was -- before it was settled.","start":426.804,"stop":438.592,"duration":11.79},{"text":"But the length of the negotiations were lengthy as indicated by that time span and they were quite intense, and there were a number of questions that arose.","start":438.592,"stop":449.052,"duration":10.46},{"text":"And to repeat my statement on answering your question before, there was never any admission of liability on the part of the insurers.","start":449.052,"stop":457.495,"duration":8.44},{"text":"Neither did they specifically deny it except that they did reject our proofs of loss.","start":457.495,"stop":466.256,"duration":8.76},{"text":"The question that’s raised by Central Tablet was of course raised for the first time in the case of United States v. Morton, an Eighth Circuit Court of Appeals’ decision decided in 1968 in which Morton which the Court of Appeals in the Eight Circuit held that insurance proceeds received after adoption of the plan of liquidation as a result of a fire occurring before that plan of liquidation were entitled of a Non-recognition Provisions of Section 337.","start":466.256,"stop":499.76,"duration":33.5},{"text":"The Circuit of Appeals judgment in this case in Central Tablet is of course directly in conflict with Morton.","start":499.76,"stop":507.837,"duration":8.08},{"text":"It also conflicts with Kinney v. the United States, which is a District Court case in California which held that in that case, the acceptance by the insurance carriers on the insured’s proof of loss was the time for the completion of the involuntary conversion by casualty and the Court further held that Section 337 applied to that case, and that the taxpayer was there too entitled to the remedial provisions of Section 337.","start":507.837,"stop":546.864,"duration":39.03},{"text":"Despite Morton and Kinney, of course, the Court of Appeals in this case as held that for the purposes of the application of Section 337 an involuntary conversion by casualty occurs in every case at the time of the casualty because this is the position of the Government here.","start":546.864,"stop":567.731,"duration":20.87},{"text":"It’s the position of the Government that an involuntary conversion by casualty is a single destructive act.","start":567.731,"stop":576.864,"duration":9.13},{"text":"It’s the contrary position of Central Tablet that and involuntary conversion by casualty is not a single destructive act but is instead a transaction which is complete for the purpose of the application for 337 when an unenforceable right to insurance proceeds arises, that’s our further position that under the facts of Central Tablet, that occurred when the insurance carriers accepted our proofs of loss.","start":576.864,"stop":612.291,"duration":35.43},{"text":"This of course is exertedly occurred following adoption of the plan of liquidation in this case.","start":612.291,"stop":621.052,"duration":8.76},{"text":"We submit that --","start":621.052,"stop":621.689,"duration":0.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Snyder, does the record show whether the fire was a -- an important fact in the decision to liquidate?","start":621.689,"stop":633.53,"duration":11.84}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, it was.","start":633.53,"stop":634.592,"duration":1.06},{"text":"The record does not show that but it was -- I don’t believe it was -- but it was in fact an important determination of the liquidation.","start":634.592,"stop":641.123,"duration":6.53}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"So that presumably, if the fire not occurred, Central Tablet would still be functioning?","start":641.123,"stop":646.327,"duration":5.2}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"I do not think I can go that far because at the time of the fire and at the time all these happened, Central Tablet was in the throes of a strike and this may have incidentally, this was one of the reasons that extended the problem with the business interruption loss, because we had to then determine when the strike might have ended had there not been a fire in order to term -- to determine the period of business interruption.","start":646.327,"stop":677.814,"duration":31.49},{"text":"So that entered into the picture, but no, I can’t see that.","start":677.814,"stop":680.203,"duration":2.39},{"text":"I think there’s no question but that.","start":680.203,"stop":682.752,"duration":2.55},{"text":"The fact of the fire was an important element in determining whether or not the corporation was eventually -- it was to go on a business, but it was not the only fact.","start":682.752,"stop":690.823,"duration":8.07}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But I guess the Government’s position is even if the liquidation was forced by the fire, that the event was still before the plan was adopted.","start":690.823,"stop":704.416,"duration":13.59}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I think that the Government’s position is factual as I understand it.","start":704.416,"stop":710.257,"duration":5.84},{"text":"But the time of an involuntary --","start":710.257,"stop":711.85,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And that the --","start":711.85,"stop":712.7,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Its always at the time of the casualty.","start":712.7,"stop":714.187,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That the tax would -- the gain would not be recognized if there was a voluntary liquidation but it would be recognized if there was a compelled one.","start":714.187,"stop":727.302,"duration":13.12}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it seems to me --","start":727.302,"stop":728.311,"duration":1.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That seems to be their position.","start":728.311,"stop":729.638,"duration":1.33}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"It seems to me that that is where the Government comes out, yes.","start":729.638,"stop":732.665,"duration":3.03},{"text":"But I suppose that they better speak to that.","start":732.665,"stop":737.444,"duration":4.78}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":737.444,"stop":738.612,"duration":1.17},{"text":"I take it, you feel the Morton Case is indistinguishable from this one factually?","start":738.612,"stop":747.267,"duration":8.66}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it is not indistinguishable factually in that in Morton, the taxpayer was at cash, and the cash basis in the Central Tablet, we are on accrual basis.","start":747.267,"stop":759.851,"duration":12.58},{"text":"But I think that the reasoning of Morton applies here that I think that Morton was correctly decided on the basis of a cash basis taxpayer.","start":759.851,"stop":773.232,"duration":13.38},{"text":"I think that Morton might have, having the case of an accrual basis taxpayer as Central Tablet might conclude that Central Tablet would have to report.","start":773.232,"stop":784.86,"duration":11.63},{"text":"Of course now, we’re talking about 337 and were -- but for the purposes of accounting that the accrual was at the time that the proofs of loss of Central Tablet were accepted by the insurers rather than as withheld, in that case, that it wasn’t until receipt of the proceeds of insurance that it was even --","start":784.86,"stop":810.878,"duration":26.02}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Is it fair to say that being on the accrual basis makes your case a little harder than for the taxpayer in Morton?","start":810.878,"stop":818.896,"duration":8.02}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I suppose.","start":818.896,"stop":819.746,"duration":0.85},{"text":"In fairness, it is except that I think under the facts of Central Tablet is distinguished of the -- distinguished from the facts of Morton and the facts of Kinney, I think we have the easier case.","start":819.746,"stop":832.596,"duration":12.85}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"But did you say that an accrual basis taxpayer would accrue this loss in the year in which the proofs of loss were accepted?","start":832.596,"stop":842.684,"duration":10.09}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I think you could -- I think you could come to that conclusion, yes, because I think with that time, and enforceable right to insurance proceeds occurs and I think probably at that time, you could also determine that the amount is reasonably determined.","start":842.684,"stop":856.065,"duration":13.38}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"I thought that -- I thought you accrued losses in the year they occurred or that the event occurred that the loss actually that the impact was on --","start":856.065,"stop":863.339,"duration":7.27}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I don’t think so.","start":863.339,"stop":864.295,"duration":0.96},{"text":"No, That’s not my understanding --","start":864.295,"stop":864.667,"duration":0.37}]},{"speakerName":"William O. Douglas","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, do you think your case is just as easy as --","start":864.667,"stop":868.118,"duration":3.45}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"I think it is, yes.","start":868.118,"stop":870.083,"duration":1.96},{"text":"I think it is.","start":870.083,"stop":874.756,"duration":4.67}]},{"speakerName":"Potter Stewart","textObjs":[{"text":"What about the condemnation cases?","start":874.756,"stop":876.668,"duration":1.91},{"text":"Do you take comfort from them or despair?","start":876.668,"stop":881.075,"duration":4.41}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the condemnation cases of course are the cases that the government relies heavily on.","start":881.075,"stop":890.367,"duration":9.29},{"text":"Frankly, I think they misplaced reliance on the condemnation cases.","start":890.367,"stop":897.217,"duration":6.85},{"text":"All of the cases they cite and all of the cases that are litigated of course, are those cases which occur under the quick take statutes or in jurisdictions in which it is held that the takes occurs at the preliminary filing of the declaration of condemnation or whatever it might be.","start":897.217,"stop":915.376,"duration":18.16},{"text":"I think if you examine the majority of statutes or the majority of jurisdictions, you’ll see that the take doesn’t occur normally until there’s a deposit made in Court or until it sometimes, there’s an actual -- a decree or a verdict.","start":915.376,"stop":929.978,"duration":14.6},{"text":"And I think when you analyze those condemnation cases against this involuntary conversion by casualty, you will see that the take is the significant part in the condemnation case because it is at that time that the right to compensation arises, and that’s the basis of holding that it’s the time of taking that a condemnation occurs.","start":929.978,"stop":957.323,"duration":27.35},{"text":"If you look at the similar event, an involuntary conversion by casualty, I believe you have to come to the conclusion that that’s going to be comparatively when the right to insurance proceeds arises.","start":957.323,"stop":973.863,"duration":16.54},{"text":"And we submit of course and it’s the basis of our case that that does not occur until at least the proofs of loss are accepted by the insurer.","start":973.863,"stop":985.183,"duration":11.32}]},{"speakerName":"Thurgood Marshall","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Snyder, what is the procedure under Ohio Law for what do you call a quick take in that kind of condemnation?","start":985.183,"stop":992.829,"duration":7.65}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, what most jurisdictions, Your Honor.","start":992.829,"stop":995.165,"duration":2.34},{"text":"There are a number of statutes, some of which the filing of the complaint or the petition will -- is held to be the time of the taking for the purposes of entry in the right of the Government to take possession.","start":995.165,"stop":1012.475,"duration":17.31},{"text":"There are other statutes however -- there are other statutes in which the time of the take is not in term of deposit.","start":1012.475,"stop":1019.59,"duration":7.12},{"text":"A deposit is placed in Court by the condemnor.","start":1019.59,"stop":1025.271,"duration":5.68}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Is the owner of the property notified?","start":1025.271,"stop":1029.571,"duration":4.3}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"I beg your pardon?","start":1029.571,"stop":1030.474,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Does the owner of the property receive notice and have an opportunity to be ahead before his property is taken?","start":1030.474,"stop":1037.967,"duration":7.49}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"No, he receives notice but there is no hearing on the -- there’s no preliminary hearing.","start":1037.967,"stop":1042.852,"duration":4.88},{"text":"There is a statutory procedure whereby you can challenge the power of the authority or the authority of the condemnor to institute this proceeding, but that’s after the take.","start":1042.852,"stop":1059.047,"duration":16.19},{"text":"I suppose it would be likened if that procedure were utilized, it would be likened to have sort of a condition subsequent to the take.","start":1059.047,"stop":1066.64,"duration":7.59}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I think we do better than that in Virginia.","start":1066.64,"stop":1071.259,"duration":4.62},{"text":"But there is a deposit, isn’t there?","start":1071.259,"stop":1074.976,"duration":3.72}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":1074.976,"stop":1075.826,"duration":0.85}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"They have the State’s estimate of the value?","start":1075.826,"stop":1077.95,"duration":2.12}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"The estate’s estimate of the value is always deposited, yes.","start":1077.95,"stop":1079.862,"duration":1.91}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"But she can do it now?","start":1079.862,"stop":1082.145,"duration":2.28}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, but very rarely of course, do they, but that has nothing to do with the substance in effect.","start":1082.145,"stop":1088.358,"duration":6.21}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"And if he doesn’t take it down that draws interest -- and award draws interest from the date of take?","start":1088.358,"stop":1095.261,"duration":6.9}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"I assume so.","start":1095.261,"stop":1098.128,"duration":2.87},{"text":"Yes, pretty I’m not sure.","start":1098.128,"stop":1099.668,"duration":1.54}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Could you take it down and still litigate for more?","start":1099.668,"stop":1102.376,"duration":2.71}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t believe so.","start":1102.376,"stop":1103.226,"duration":0.85},{"text":"No, I think if you take it down, that ends the question of the reasonable value of the property which has been taken by the condemning authority.","start":1103.226,"stop":1117.031,"duration":13.8}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Are you drawing any distinction from the State condemnation on a federal one?","start":1117.031,"stop":1120.642,"duration":3.61}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"No, because I think that like the State, to my knowledge is that they’re under Federal Law, there are a number of statutory procedures, one or two of which are quick take in which at the time of -- a matter of fact, I don’t even think you have to file a Court proceeding.","start":1120.642,"stop":1138.817,"duration":18.17},{"text":"What I think at the time of the take, which is at the -- almost the earliest point of the condemnation, the right to compensation arises.","start":1138.817,"stop":1149.595,"duration":10.78},{"text":"But you could say that basis that you can justify these quick take statutes as I read the decisions of this Court with some basic concept of Constitutional Law, I think the right has to arise then where the statute is not invalidly applied.","start":1149.595,"stop":1165.684,"duration":16.09}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"We’ll resume that in the morning.","start":1165.684,"stop":1166.905,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you, sir.","start":1166.905,"stop":1168.923,"duration":2.02}]}]},{"transcriptTitle":"Oral Argument - March 26, 1974","transcriptLink":"https://apps.oyez.org/player/#/burger4/oral_argument_audio/16073","transcript":[{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, you may resume arguments in Central Tablet Manufacturing against the United States.","start":0,"stop":13.747,"duration":13.75},{"text":"Mr. Snyder, you may resume.","start":13.747,"stop":19.314,"duration":5.57}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court, to summarize Central Tablet versus the United States.","start":19.314,"stop":27.378,"duration":8.06},{"text":"The question is whether an involuntary conversion by casualty for the purposes of the application of Section 337 occurs at the point of the casualty which in this case preceded the doctrine of the plan liquidation, or whether instead it occurs at the point that a non-conditional obligation to pay insurance proceeds on the part of the insurance carriers arises, which in this case post-dated adoption of the plan of liquidation.","start":27.378,"stop":61.584,"duration":34.21},{"text":"I stated yesterday, it’s the position of the government that an involuntary conversion by casualty for the purposes of the application on Section 337 occurs in every case at the point of the casualty, and that an involuntary conversion by casualty is a single destructive event.","start":61.584,"stop":84.204,"duration":22.62},{"text":"It’s our contrary position that an involuntary conversion by casualty is a gain or loss producing transaction.","start":84.204,"stop":93.786,"duration":9.58},{"text":"And that the purposes of Section 337, that transaction is complete on an enforceable right to ensure its proceeds arises.","start":93.786,"stop":108.05,"duration":14.26},{"text":"We submit that the casualty is much like an executory contract of sale.","start":108.05,"stop":116.172,"duration":8.12},{"text":"In an executory contract of sale by treasury regulation, it is distinguished from a contract of sale.","start":116.172,"stop":123.505,"duration":7.33},{"text":"A contract of sale in turn is defined as a contract in which there is an obligation on the part of the buyer to buy, and an obligation on the part of the seller to sell.","start":123.505,"stop":136.403,"duration":12.9},{"text":"And, if it is not until there those obligations with the sale under treasury regulation is complete for the purposes of the application of Section 337.","start":136.403,"stop":147.752,"duration":11.35},{"text":"And, we submit that the comparable event, the taxable event to that sale is an involuntary conversion when enforceable right to proceeds arises.","start":147.752,"stop":164.262,"duration":16.51}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Can I ask you what difference this makes this case, which it is held to be.","start":164.262,"stop":172.496,"duration":8.23}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"What difference this makes in this case, are you talking about dollar difference?","start":172.496,"stop":180.47,"duration":7.97}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That and what -- the --","start":180.47,"stop":181.686,"duration":1.22}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it makes approximately --","start":181.686,"stop":185.436,"duration":3.75}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, there would be two taxes.","start":185.436,"stop":188.119,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Two taxes.","start":188.119,"stop":189.624,"duration":1.5}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"One on the corporation and one on the --","start":189.624,"stop":191.967,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, there would be two taxes, one on the corporation and one on the stockholders.","start":191.967,"stop":196.818,"duration":4.85}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What is the rate on the corporation?","start":196.818,"stop":199.161,"duration":2.34}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t know of here.","start":199.161,"stop":204.171,"duration":5.01}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It would not be --","start":204.171,"stop":205.157,"duration":0.99},{"text":"would not be the regular corporate rate?","start":205.157,"stop":207.84,"duration":2.68}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh! Yes, it would be at the regular corporate rate.","start":207.84,"stop":210.044,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And, the rate of the shareholders would vary.","start":210.044,"stop":213.266,"duration":3.22}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Would be vary depending on their shares, but yes, that’s the difference.","start":213.266,"stop":218.514,"duration":5.25},{"text":"I thought you were asking about --","start":218.514,"stop":220.099,"duration":1.58}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":220.099,"stop":221.534,"duration":1.44}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, there will be two taxes, one on the corporation and factor has been on tax of the corporation, this is a refund.","start":221.534,"stop":228.182,"duration":6.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What was -- what was the refund thing?","start":228.182,"stop":230.046,"duration":1.86}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"That was $80,000.00, now some part of that was a business interruption in charge with the question which it is not before this Court, it was not taken on appeal, but I would say approximately $70,000.00 is in issue here, and that’s the tax to the corporation which was paid under protest.","start":230.046,"stop":251.753,"duration":21.71},{"text":"And of course there is a tax due that the time of a liquidation of the assets in the distribution of those assets to the stockholders.","start":251.753,"stop":262.331,"duration":10.58},{"text":"This is of course a point that has already been complete.","start":262.331,"stop":265.615,"duration":3.28}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Snyder, what do you regard as the purpose of Section 337?","start":265.615,"stop":271.801,"duration":6.19}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it’s a remedial provision.","start":271.801,"stop":274.484,"duration":2.68},{"text":"I think the purpose is to eliminate this kind of double tax in the situation in which there’s a single really gain or loss producing transaction.","start":274.484,"stop":286.786,"duration":12.3},{"text":"We’re talking about the gains.","start":286.786,"stop":288.892,"duration":2.11},{"text":"You have the same gain producing track transaction.","start":288.892,"stop":292.772,"duration":3.88},{"text":"I think the purpose of the statute is to eliminate a tax from that single transaction on both the corporation and the stockholders when distribution is made in liquidation within the period of 12 months.","start":292.772,"stop":308.408,"duration":15.64}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"How does your position here give weight or force to that purpose?","start":308.408,"stop":317.145,"duration":8.74}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"How does it give weight or force to that purpose?","start":317.145,"stop":319.468,"duration":2.32},{"text":"Well, because under the facts of this case it would clearly fall within that.","start":319.468,"stop":323.989,"duration":4.52},{"text":"There would be a tax on the corporation and a tax on the stockholder.","start":323.989,"stop":327.201,"duration":3.21}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, two or not but of course your casualty, it happened before the decision to liquidate have taken place.","start":327.201,"stop":335.232,"duration":8.03}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"The casualty happened, yes.","start":335.232,"stop":337.118,"duration":1.89},{"text":"But I distinguish between the casualty and an involuntary conversion.","start":337.118,"stop":341.21,"duration":4.09},{"text":"Well, I think, the statutes in treasury regulations distinguish between a casualty loss and an involuntary conversion.","start":341.21,"stop":349.53,"duration":8.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, wasn’t it the purpose of the statute as you say to enable corporations in this kind of a tax situation, as your corporation was with a low base to liquidate but of the hazards implied by the Court case, under the one that came down later depending on a slight difference in factual setup.","start":349.53,"stop":374.422,"duration":24.89},{"text":"I was wondering, when this casualty is thrown upon you, and as you indicated yesterday was a vital factor in the decisions of liquidate rather than to carry on whether your posture here for on accrual basis taxpayer sponsoring that statutory purpose in anyway.","start":374.422,"stop":394.913,"duration":20.49}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, because I can do no more than repeat my attempt to an answer before which is that this is the same kind of transaction.","start":394.913,"stop":406.576,"duration":11.66},{"text":"The 337 was obviously on the surface designed to meet what is the difference between a casualty and on executory contract of sale.","start":406.576,"stop":418.861,"duration":12.28},{"text":"The only difference is its thrust upon this taxpayer, he has no choice or it has no choice.","start":418.861,"stop":425.518,"duration":6.66},{"text":"In an ordinary sale or an exchange, the taxpayer can take his own time in maneuvering negotiate, and then still has the remedial of fact of Section 377, that on an equity basis, I think it’s more equitable to include an involuntary conversion by casualties or this ordinary sale.","start":425.518,"stop":454.947,"duration":29.43},{"text":"Mr. Chief justice I would like to resume on the remaining time for rebuttal.","start":454.947,"stop":458.011,"duration":3.06}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Very Well Mr. Snyder.","start":458.011,"stop":463.197,"duration":5.19},{"text":"Mr. Smith","start":463.197,"stop":465.58,"duration":2.38}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Chief Justice and may it please the Court.","start":465.58,"stop":468.454,"duration":2.87},{"text":"I think it would be useful for the Court to focus on the text of this statute, which is set fort on page two of petitioner’s brief.","start":468.454,"stop":478.739,"duration":10.28},{"text":"The statute provides that one, if a corporation adopts the plan of complete liquidation and then two, with in a 12-month period beginning on the date of the adoption of the plan, all of its assets are distributed in complete liquidation to it shareholders.","start":478.739,"stop":498.303,"duration":19.56},{"text":"Then and only then shall no a gain or loss be recognized to the corporation from the sale or exchange by it of property within the 12-month period.","start":498.303,"stop":510.794,"duration":12.49},{"text":"Statute mandates a particular time sequence of events.","start":510.794,"stop":516.381,"duration":5.59},{"text":"First, a plan must be adopted thereby identifying the corporation as one which is commencing a liquidation process.","start":516.381,"stop":526.707,"duration":10.33},{"text":"Secondly, once the plan is adopted, then a 12-month period begins to commence running forward in time.","start":526.707,"stop":535.658,"duration":8.95},{"text":"The statute is a strict statute, it’s so far as sales or exchanges occurring before the adoption of the plan or sales or exchanges occurring after the 12-month period has run cannot be protected by the non recognition provisions of the statute.","start":535.658,"stop":555.898,"duration":20.24},{"text":"Now, here, the sequence of events which have occurred in this transaction demonstrate that it is exactly the reverse of the situation that Congress intended to benefit by the statute.","start":555.898,"stop":569.179,"duration":13.28},{"text":"Because first, we have here the file on September 10, 1965, at that point in time, the taxpayer did not evidence any intension to liquidate, indeed it has been discussed the file itself prompted the decision to liquidate in part because a major asset of a corporation was destroyed.","start":569.179,"stop":590.052,"duration":20.87},{"text":"Then some more than eight months later on May 14th 1966, petitioner adopted a plan of complete liquidation by action of its Board of Directors and presumably by ratification of its shareholders.","start":590.052,"stop":604.635,"duration":14.58},{"text":"Now, in order to place the gain accruing from the insurance proceeds, the petitioner must somehow place that gain after the adoption of the plan that is after May 14th 1966.","start":604.635,"stop":620.754,"duration":16.12},{"text":"For it arises before, the statute cannot apply.","start":620.754,"stop":624.465,"duration":3.71},{"text":"Now, it does this by arguing that what has occurred here after the plan was somewhat like in negotiation of sale, it dickered with the insurance company over the amount of the award, and ultimately, that was concluded sometime in August, after the adoption of the plan.","start":624.465,"stop":644.162,"duration":19.7},{"text":"But, it is plain what occurred here was not a sales negotiation in any sense that term represents.","start":644.162,"stop":651.565,"duration":7.4},{"text":"It was simply a compensation for loss which the insurance company pays pursuant to the contract of buyer insurance.","start":651.565,"stop":660.414,"duration":8.85},{"text":"This post-buyer discussions which the petitioner had with its insurance company is simply directed to the amount of the compensation, and the fact that this transaction is not a sale, it’s well settled by this Court’s decision in flack Flaccus Leather Company.","start":660.414,"stop":676.514,"duration":16.1},{"text":"Now, the fact that this is not a sale might be deemed to the end of the matter for we have a statute here that talks about a sale.","start":676.514,"stop":684.868,"duration":8.35},{"text":"But, it is not the end of the matter because two Court decisions, the Court of Claims, and that Towanda Textiles case, and the Kent Manufacturing decisions of the Fourth Circuit have included within the context of Section 337, gains from involuntary conversions such as this, that is gains from the destruction of property.","start":684.868,"stop":706.439,"duration":21.57},{"text":"But, the situation of those cases is entirely different insofar as those -- the facts that those cases can be fit within the time sequence mandated by Congress in the statute.","start":706.439,"stop":718.871,"duration":12.43},{"text":"That is that the plan occurs first and then the gain arise afterwards.","start":718.871,"stop":724.952,"duration":6.08},{"text":"Now, in the case involved in Towanda Textiles case, we had a situation where the corporation first adopted the plan of complete liquidation and then subsequent to that time, the fire occurred.","start":724.952,"stop":739.675,"duration":14.72},{"text":"In that sense, one could say, as the Court of Claims did, that the fire interrupted the liquidation process, which had already been commenced by the operation of the plan pursuant to the statute.","start":739.675,"stop":753.738,"duration":14.06},{"text":"And, it is the Court of Claims’ reason if the destruction had not occurred Towanda Textiles, the property would have been sold in the normal course of liquidation pursuant to the Section 337 plan within the 12-month period.","start":753.738,"stop":769.325,"duration":15.59}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Smith, did the Government oppose that result in the Court of Claims?","start":769.325,"stop":773.235,"duration":3.91}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"The Government opposed that result in the Court of Claims on the ground that no sale or exchange occurred.","start":773.235,"stop":780.498,"duration":7.26}]},{"speakerName":"Harry A. Blackmun","textObjs":[{"text":"Suppose we have the adoption of the plan and then fire within the 12-month period, but the final insurance settlement 15-months after the adoption of the plan.","start":780.498,"stop":792.995,"duration":12.5},{"text":"What is the Government’s position as to that?","start":792.995,"stop":795.211,"duration":2.22}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the Government’s position surely is that if all the assets of the corporation and not distributed within the 12-month period then the statute doesn’t apply, but that’s the kind of situation, Mr. Justice Blackmun which is easily remedied by a corporation in that posture simply by distributing the claim to its shareholders pro-rata.","start":795.211,"stop":817.206,"duration":22},{"text":"So, there would be no problem with that arranging for compliance with the statute.","start":817.206,"stop":823.039,"duration":5.83}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commissioner acquiesces ultimately in Towanda.","start":823.039,"stop":825.884,"duration":2.85}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"The Commissioner acquiesces to the proposition of those cases, that a sale or exchange that gains -- that Section 337 gains includes gains from involuntary conversion.","start":825.884,"stop":838.709,"duration":12.82},{"text":"But the point of those cases, Mr. Justice Rehnquist, is that the statutory time sequence was observed in those cases insofar as what the statute was meant to cover was a corporation identifying itself as a corporation in liquidation, and that without the adoption of the plan, such a corporation has not commenced a liquidation process.","start":838.709,"stop":862.816,"duration":24.11},{"text":"And I think that those cases can best be explained in terms of the reason that prompt to their result by the fact that had the fire not occurred in those cases, the corporation surely would have sold the property pursuant to the normal kind of Section 337 plan that tax practitioners are well familiar with.","start":862.816,"stop":883.23,"duration":20.41},{"text":"What we have here, at the time of the fire, the petitioner was not planning to sell its building pursuant to a plan of liquidation.","start":883.23,"stop":891.34,"duration":8.11},{"text":"Its intension to liquidate was formed after the fire, and to that extent, we feel that the plan here should not relate back to the fire anymore than a subsequently within a plan should relate back to a prior sale.","start":891.34,"stop":906.409,"duration":15.07}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What taxes are at issue here?","start":906.409,"stop":909.991,"duration":3.58},{"text":"For what year, the year of the casualty or the year of payment?","start":909.991,"stop":913.941,"duration":3.95}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"The taxes at issue here presumably of the year of the payment.","start":913.941,"stop":919.347,"duration":5.41}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Oh! You mean the Government -- do you think when a casual -- when a fire takes place in December ‘65, and the proceeds and finally paid in ‘66, and there’s a gain, the gain is accruable in ‘66.","start":919.347,"stop":938.201,"duration":18.85}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, if you are an accrual basis taxpayer and all the events have been fixed, the gain would reportable in ‘65.","start":938.201,"stop":944.709,"duration":6.51}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well that is not what your colleague stated, and this will happen, isn’t it that the taxes at issue here are ‘66 taxes or not?","start":944.709,"stop":956.169,"duration":11.46}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"I think they’re ‘66 taxes but the point of that, Mr. Justice White that simply goes to when the tax is -- when that gain is realized for the purposes of reporting [Voice Overlap].","start":956.169,"stop":968.452,"duration":12.28}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And if there had been a loss, let’s assume that there had never been -- let’s assume that the insurance proceeds didn’t pay off.","start":968.452,"stop":976.446,"duration":7.99}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":976.446,"stop":976.586,"duration":0.14}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"In other words, it didn’t pay the basis.","start":976.586,"stop":979.249,"duration":2.66},{"text":"The new building didn’t pay it, when would be the loss be approvable?","start":979.249,"stop":982.71,"duration":3.46}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"The loss would be approval presumably at a time when it became clear that the loss -- that there would be a loss.","start":982.71,"stop":989.072,"duration":6.36},{"text":"But following that point to its conclusion, I think it should be pointed out that the net effect to the taxpayer’s position, in this case would be to foreclose its recognition of a loss under such circumstances.","start":989.072,"stop":1005.27,"duration":16.2},{"text":"Because if the loss arose as of the time that the insurance company finally decided not to pay off or to pay off not an excessive basis.","start":1005.27,"stop":1017.255,"duration":11.99},{"text":"Then, petitioner’s position here that that loss should be recognized that time would result in the loss arising after the adoption of a plan.","start":1017.255,"stop":1026.887,"duration":9.63}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But, in this ordinary case where there’s no liquidation involved and there is a loss that the insurance doesn’t cover.","start":1026.887,"stop":1035.593,"duration":8.71},{"text":"I think if you suggest the loss of the approval in the year of the proceeds would be.","start":1035.593,"stop":1042.517,"duration":6.92}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, certainly for cash basis taxpayer.","start":1042.517,"stop":1045.117,"duration":2.6},{"text":"For the accrual base taxpayer, I would suggest that if it at the end of the year, let’s say on December 20, it became clear what the amount of the loss was but the check were not paid until in the next year.","start":1045.117,"stop":1055.517,"duration":10.4}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Not so here.","start":1055.517,"stop":1057.803,"duration":2.29}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Apparently not so here.","start":1057.803,"stop":1059.128,"duration":1.32}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s all right.","start":1059.128,"stop":1061.454,"duration":2.33}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Now, in view of the fact that the -- since the statute clearly would not apply to a situation where a sale took place and then the plan were adopted.","start":1061.454,"stop":1075.184,"duration":13.73},{"text":"I think that the implication of the petitioner’s position here would be -- would be to give a preference to those taxpayers suffering a destruction of property that is not available to taxpayers simply selling corporate assets in the normal course of a liquidation.","start":1075.184,"stop":1093.179,"duration":18},{"text":"Now, we think that the condemnation cases, the lines of positions involving condemnation offer a useful analogy at our on instructive as it correct results was to release -- which should be reached here.","start":1093.179,"stop":1107.51,"duration":14.33},{"text":"What we have in this mind of decisions is a uniform holdings of all the Courts of Appeals to the effect that in s condemnation situation where the taking of the property takes place prior to the adoption of a plan of liquidation.","start":1107.51,"stop":1126.173,"duration":18.66},{"text":"Then, the gain from that condemnation cannot be covered by Section 337 because the plan arose afterwards.","start":1126.173,"stop":1135.076,"duration":8.9},{"text":"Now, this is the holdings of these cases not withstanding the fact that a condemnation proceeding may be litigated for several years, and the exact amount of the award may not be fixed for several years.","start":1135.076,"stop":1148.938,"duration":13.86}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Don’t you know at the time of taking under most State Law and under Federal Law have the right to draw down at least the right of the amount that condemners deposited so that you get some cash proceeds?","start":1148.938,"stop":1161.459,"duration":12.52}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Justice Rehnquist, the situations are varied under both Federal and State Condemnation proceedings.","start":1161.459,"stop":1168.942,"duration":7.48},{"text":"We saw the case called Dwight versus United States, a Second Circuit case which involved a State Condemnation.","start":1168.942,"stop":1176.579,"duration":7.64},{"text":"In that situation is very much like a sudden event of fire. The Board of Estimate of New York City simply filed a damage map in the Court, and that resulted in the taking of property.","start":1176.579,"stop":1190.063,"duration":13.48},{"text":"To let the condemnation proceeding to fix the amount of the just compensation stretched over many years without any payment.","start":1190.063,"stop":1199.392,"duration":9.33},{"text":"And Second Circuit held in that case that notwithstanding, the fact that the condemnation was sudden and that the petitioner there could not -- the taxpayer there could not even finely adopt the plan even it had known of the -- because it did not know the event still, Section 337 did not apply to insulate these gains from corporate taxation.","start":1199.392,"stop":1221.764,"duration":22.37},{"text":"And, there are other Federal Condemnation situations notably in the Likins-Foster Honolulu case which we cite, where there are deposits that paid in before then the condemnee can draw down on it.","start":1221.764,"stop":1233.611,"duration":11.85},{"text":"But, I think that the situation -- the situation sufficiently vary that you can’t really make a general rule about the practice on the condemnation proceedings.","start":1233.611,"stop":1245.878,"duration":12.27},{"text":"When the Second Circuit considered the Dwight case, it was based with the situation far more, shall we say “harsh” than this case, because the Board of Estimate simply filed this damage map, and that was the end of the matter.","start":1245.878,"stop":1260.31,"duration":14.43},{"text":"The taxpayer simply did not have time to adopt the plan of complete liquidation.","start":1260.31,"stop":1265.398,"duration":5.09},{"text":"The Second Circuit simply said the statute has strict requirements and if it is to be modified to cover all gains from involuntary conversions then Congress has to modify the statute.","start":1265.398,"stop":1277.312,"duration":11.91},{"text":"As we point out in our brief, an advisory commission in 1959, so urge Congress to modify the statute to cover all gains from involuntary conversions whether they arise before -- whether the event arises before or after the adoption of the plan and Congress did not act on this proposal.","start":1277.312,"stop":1299.487,"duration":22.18},{"text":"So, what you have here is a situation where taxpayers subjected to sudden events such as condemnation, clearly cannot have the benefit of this statute if they do not abide by the statutory time sequence of first adopting the plan and then within the 12-months experiencing this event.","start":1299.487,"stop":1321.558,"duration":22.07},{"text":"What the taxpayer’s position here would lead to, we submit, would be a situation where taxpayers suffering destruction of insured property would be accorded to preference of a taxpayer’s suffering a sudden condemnation very similar to what happened in the Dwight case.","start":1321.558,"stop":1338.679,"duration":17.12},{"text":"Now, what petitioner attempts to distinguished these condemnation cases, it says, condemnation creates an enforceable obligation to pay a certain amount of just compensation by the condemning authority.","start":1338.679,"stop":1352.773,"duration":14.09},{"text":"But, the destruction of its insured property here gave rise, so it says, to simply a conditional or contingent claim.","start":1352.773,"stop":1361.816,"duration":9.04},{"text":"But what are these contingencies that the taxpayer is relying upon to base its arguments to push forward to this positive event after the adoption of a plan in there.","start":1361.816,"stop":1374.343,"duration":12.53},{"text":"It talks about the filing of a notice of loss, it talks about the filing of a proof of loss, and it talks about other proof complying with other procedural requirements under the contract of insurance.","start":1374.343,"stop":1386.96,"duration":12.62},{"text":"But the record here indicates that these procedural requirements had already been met by petitioner prior to the adoption of the plan.","start":1386.96,"stop":1397.171,"duration":10.21},{"text":"For example, a record indicates here that negotiation where the fire started, fire was on September 10th,1965, the negotiations that the petitioner commenced with insurance property began as early as October 8, 1965.","start":1397.171,"stop":1411.153,"duration":13.98},{"text":"In fact, petitioner’s own counsel in the District Court, testify that the proof of loss in this case was filed prior to December 1965, again prior to the adoption of the plan.","start":1411.153,"stop":1423.407,"duration":12.25},{"text":"Petitioner does not meet its own proposed test, and that is the test proposed by the District Court in Kinney case on which it relied.","start":1423.407,"stop":1432.361,"duration":8.95},{"text":"But in any event, we don’t think that these procedural requirements under the insurance contract create the claim against the insurance company because just as a condemnation taking creates the claim under -- against the condemning authority.","start":1432.361,"stop":1451.795,"duration":19.43},{"text":"So thus, the destructive event of the fire, we submit, creates the claim against the insurance company.","start":1451.795,"stop":1458.063,"duration":6.27},{"text":"But as this irrevocable event of either taking by condemnation or by fire, which converts the property into the obligation running against the insurance company go with the authority.","start":1458.063,"stop":1470.469,"duration":12.41}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Would it make any difference to your submission if the casualty occurred in the absence of insurance and yet the owner of the building, for example which burned, so it had been caused by the negligence of someone whom he intended to sue, so that there was no contractual right arguably of any right to recover?","start":1470.469,"stop":1501.512,"duration":31.04},{"text":"In other words, suppose the only claim was the contingent negligence suit, would that make any difference?","start":1501.512,"stop":1508.827,"duration":7.32}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"I don’t think it should make any difference, Mr. Justice Powell.","start":1508.827,"stop":1511.542,"duration":2.71},{"text":"I think what you have here is a -- in effect an irrevocable transformation of property from a property which exists to a property which has been destroyed, and that creates in the case -- of your case of negligence, the case creates an obligation on the on the common law, I suppose for recompense, which will not elevate it to a contractual claim would nevertheless still represent the claim against the negligent party.","start":1511.542,"stop":1538.415,"duration":26.87},{"text":"I don’t think that should make a difference.","start":1538.415,"stop":1540.611,"duration":2.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I suppose, in my brother Powell’s hypothetical case, in the year of the fire, that would be a casualty loss to the corporation, wouldn’t it?","start":1540.611,"stop":1549.624,"duration":9.01}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be a casualty loss to the corporation.","start":1549.624,"stop":1551.989,"duration":2.37},{"text":"Yes.","start":1551.989,"stop":1552.049,"duration":0.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And then a the year of the -- any subsequent year of recovery, it would be ordinary --","start":1552.049,"stop":1557.575,"duration":5.53}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"I can say that is -- well, it would be a casualty and loss unless it was covered under another provision Section 1231 of the code, which provides for netting of losses on involuntary conversions against gains which from the sale of capital assets.","start":1557.575,"stop":1579.169,"duration":21.59},{"text":"So, I don’t think I could answer completely that that would be, you know, an ordinary loss, but if there were no other gains presumably it would be an ordinary one.","start":1579.169,"stop":1589.5,"duration":10.33}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be --","start":1589.5,"stop":1590.319,"duration":0.82}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Absent such --","start":1590.319,"stop":1591.415,"duration":1.1}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"It would be a casualty loss that’s an ordinary loss.","start":1591.415,"stop":1594.796,"duration":3.38},{"text":"It’s not going to be under a capital loss --","start":1594.796,"stop":1597.391,"duration":2.6}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":1597.391,"stop":1598.977,"duration":1.59},{"text":"Having such details and is depreciation of the kind.","start":1598.977,"stop":1601.869,"duration":2.89}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Right, and then in my brother Powell’s case in a subsequent year, the corporation should get a judgment against the negligent person who caused the fire, but will the tax apply beyond that?","start":1601.869,"stop":1620.774,"duration":18.9}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"They have to take that into income.","start":1620.774,"stop":1622.598,"duration":1.82}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Ordinary income.","start":1622.598,"stop":1625.423,"duration":2.83}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s the principle --","start":1625.423,"stop":1626.818,"duration":1.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, his question was what if the corporation was under a 12-month plan of liquidation at the time of the recovery?","start":1626.818,"stop":1638.478,"duration":11.66}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"If we are on a 12-month plan of liquidation at the time of the recovery, I think that this question as to when you take something in to income are wholly a part from the question as to whether the plan applies.","start":1638.478,"stop":1652.062,"duration":13.58},{"text":"I mean, if the casualty occurred prior to the Law, let’s say in the middle of the plan of complete liquidation then presumably, if that were a loss, that would be an uninsured loss, so to speak, then you would have a loss that wouldn’t be recognized.","start":1652.062,"stop":1670.691,"duration":18.63},{"text":"Isn’t that right?","start":1670.691,"stop":1671.188,"duration":0.5},{"text":"Because it would carry after the plan.","start":1671.188,"stop":1673.414,"duration":2.23}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"I guess so.","start":1673.414,"stop":1674.65,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"So then, in the subsequent year when you get money into income since you have not deducted that loss, presumably, I would imagine that that should have to be taken into income since I can’t think of any reason why it shouldn’t.","start":1674.65,"stop":1693.504,"duration":18.85}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But maybe only the net over the loss.","start":1693.504,"stop":1695.81,"duration":2.31}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, well, this raises a question as to whether you are -- I suppose under the tax benefit rule, if you had not got any tax benefit from the loss, you don’t have to take that it into income.","start":1695.81,"stop":1707.572,"duration":11.76},{"text":"I was imagining it would be only the net of the loss, I think that’s right.","start":1707.572,"stop":1712.103,"duration":4.53},{"text":"Now, we think that this subsequent events upon which petitioner relies, that is its negotiations with the insurance company, its compliance with the procedural requirements of the policy simply go if an aid of the collection of the claim.","start":1712.103,"stop":1728.205,"duration":16.1},{"text":"They do not create the claim against the insurance company.","start":1728.205,"stop":1731.696,"duration":3.49},{"text":"Now, while the taxpayer recognizes that this transaction is not a sale here, it argues that into its reply brief, it has many of the characteristics of a sale.","start":1731.696,"stop":1742.988,"duration":11.29},{"text":"What it says in effect is the insurance award is analogous to a sales price, and it assumes that you cannot have a sale without a determinable sales price.","start":1742.988,"stop":1753.117,"duration":10.13},{"text":"Well, this assumption which was made by the Morton opinion as well, we think is erroneous.","start":1753.117,"stop":1760.111,"duration":6.99},{"text":"There are many instances where you can have a sale not only for tax purposes but for any purpose without the existence of the determinable sales prices.","start":1760.111,"stop":1768.881,"duration":8.77},{"text":"For example, a business can be sold for a percentage of future profits over a stated period of time, and the sales price in that situation is not determinable until the end of the period.","start":1768.881,"stop":1782.915,"duration":14.03},{"text":"But no one would doubt it, there were a transfer of the benefits and burdens of ownership to that business, that there was a sale, clearly a sale occurs in that case.","start":1782.915,"stop":1792.538,"duration":9.62},{"text":"And to that extent, we think that the petitioner’s analogy is false.","start":1792.538,"stop":1797.566,"duration":5.03},{"text":"Alternatively, the taxpayer argues here that the payment by the insurance company could be a sale.","start":1797.566,"stop":1803.961,"duration":6.39},{"text":"It talks about a situation where the insurance company will pay an adjustment for salvage, and presumably take over the ownership of the property.","start":1803.961,"stop":1812.826,"duration":8.87},{"text":"Now, first of all, there’s no showing that it has occurred here, it didn’t occur here.","start":1812.826,"stop":1817.145,"duration":4.32},{"text":"Well, this payment was simply compensation for a loss, but even if there was -- even in such a situation, we think that the compensation for the loss element of the payment would not be analogous to a sales price, so to speak, because that simply is a payment for a decrease in value of the damaged property, value which has disappeared.","start":1817.145,"stop":1838.839,"duration":21.69},{"text":"That is -- can in no way, be analogize to an element of the payment which would be in the sales price.","start":1838.839,"stop":1847.049,"duration":8.21},{"text":"And finally, as we point out in greater detail in our brief, we think that the net effect of the petitioner’s position here is contrary to settled rules governing the holding period of property.","start":1847.049,"stop":1860,"duration":12.95},{"text":"Almost 40 years ago, this Court held in the McPhee case, that holding period -- the concept of holding period is coterminous with the concept of ownership.","start":1860,"stop":1870.87,"duration":10.87},{"text":"And, as corollary to those cases, there are other cases which hold, that when property is destroyed, its holding period ends.","start":1870.87,"stop":1879.969,"duration":9.1},{"text":"Now, those holdings were rendered in a situations involving sunken ships, but the lesson is equally instructive here.","start":1879.969,"stop":1890.239,"duration":10.27},{"text":"In those cases, a taxpayer board a ship on January 1st and then it sunk on March 1st, to use the example.","start":1890.239,"stop":1899.475,"duration":9.24},{"text":"The insurance proceeds however were not paid until July 15, and what the taxpayers in those cases argued was that the holding period -- their holding period should be stretched forward beyond six months to the point where the insurance proceeds were paid and in that way, to try to get long term capital gain.","start":1899.475,"stop":1922.569,"duration":23.09},{"text":"Now, the Court rejected that notion.","start":1922.569,"stop":1924.633,"duration":2.06},{"text":"The holding period ended when the ship sunk, when the destructive event occur.","start":1924.633,"stop":1930.29,"duration":5.66},{"text":"So, we think that the -- we think that those holdings are instructive as to the error that petitioners making in this argument.","start":1930.29,"stop":1938.522,"duration":8.23},{"text":"Because if petitioner’s argument is right that its so called “sale” under the statute did not occur until the insurance proceeds were paid, the implication of its argument is that a sale occurred long before after its coterminous holding period, an ownership have ended.","start":1938.522,"stop":1958.022,"duration":19.5},{"text":"We think that’s wrong and we think that that’s simply another demonstration of the error of petitioner’s position and the reason why the Court’s judgment at Court of Appeals should be affirmed.","start":1958.022,"stop":1969.168,"duration":11.15},{"text":"I have nothing further to say if the Court has no further questions.","start":1969.168,"stop":1972.27,"duration":3.1}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"May I ask you another question, let us assume that the proceeds to this prior had been received by the party whose property was burned and he had plan to, and did carry on the plan of reconstructing the destroyed building.","start":1972.27,"stop":1995.619,"duration":23.35},{"text":"Let’s assume the proceeds received within the statutory period that permits them to be received for reconstruction purposes were their recognition of gain.","start":1995.619,"stop":2006.879,"duration":11.26}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Section 1033","start":2006.879,"stop":2008.115,"duration":1.24}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"1033, right, then let’s assume that the day after the building that reconstructed, a plan of liquidation was adopted, would there be any problem with that?","start":2008.115,"stop":2019.693,"duration":11.58}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"And then the property was sold?","start":2019.693,"stop":2021.178,"duration":1.49}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes.","start":2021.178,"stop":2021.877,"duration":0.7}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"I presumably, I don’t think there would be a problem because what you got there is simply the property sold after the adoption of the plan.","start":2021.877,"stop":2030.895,"duration":9.02},{"text":"The fact that it took advantage of another provision of the Internal Revenue Code to reconstruct the property, and get a carry of the basis, I don’t think it would present any problem.","start":2030.895,"stop":2041.067,"duration":10.17}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"You end up with what might be regarded as substantially the same result, don’t you?","start":2041.067,"stop":2045.506,"duration":4.44}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Substantially the same result, yes.","start":2045.506,"stop":2047.59,"duration":2.08},{"text":"But in the situation you posited, I think, Mr. Justice Powell, that the statutory time sequence in Section 337 is observed and so far as the property is restore, then the plan is adopted and then the property is sold.","start":2047.59,"stop":2066.237,"duration":18.65}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"I understand that.","start":2066.237,"stop":2067.184,"duration":0.95}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"In many ways, a Federal Tax factor, that didn’t occur here.","start":2067.184,"stop":2073.052,"duration":5.87}]},{"speakerName":"Lewis F. Powell, Jr.","textObjs":[{"text":"The Government just really wants to put the taxpayer all in that trouble, does it?","start":2073.052,"stop":2076.893,"duration":3.84}]},{"speakerName":"Stuart A. Smith","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, I mean, we view the statutory requirements as precise.","start":2076.893,"stop":2084.032,"duration":7.14},{"text":"It is a cliché but nevertheless, a somewhat with a ring of truth to it that you can’t be judged for federal tax purposes on the basis of what you didn’t or what they didn’t do that here.","start":2084.032,"stop":2096.23,"duration":12.2},{"text":"I have nothing further to say.","start":2096.23,"stop":2100.22,"duration":3.99}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, briefly --","start":2100.22,"stop":2108.766,"duration":8.55},{"text":"Counsel professed his argument with a reference to the strict time sequence required by the statute, and he also this argument largely in the same vein.","start":2108.766,"stop":2118.623,"duration":9.86},{"text":"And with that in mind, I would like to read Treasury of Regulation 14437-2A which says, “In ascertaining whether a sale or exchange occurs on or after the date in which the plan of complete liquidation has adopted the fact that negotiations were sale may have been commenced either by the corporation or insurer.” All of those are both shall be disregarded.","start":2118.623,"stop":2144.815,"duration":26.19},{"text":"Moreover, in executory contract to sell is to be distinguished from the contract of sale.","start":2144.815,"stop":2149.696,"duration":4.88},{"text":"Ordinarily, a sale has not occurred when a contract to sell has been entered into but title and possession of the property have not been transferred.","start":2149.696,"stop":2159.248,"duration":9.55},{"text":"And this is the strict time sequence that counsel refers to.","start":2159.248,"stop":2164.725,"duration":5.48},{"text":"The Government is committed to the proposition because it acquiesce by revenue ruling in it that an involuntary conversion by casualty is of sale or exchange, so it has to be treated that way, but they want to treat it differently.","start":2164.725,"stop":2178.338,"duration":13.61},{"text":"They want to treat it differently from a sale.","start":2178.338,"stop":2181.54,"duration":3.2},{"text":"They want to treat it as a single destructive event which it is not.","start":2181.54,"stop":2185.72,"duration":4.18},{"text":"The whole thrust, the whole purpose of the Internal Revenue Code of Income Taxes is directed to the realization of gain or loss.","start":2185.72,"stop":2198.556,"duration":12.84},{"text":"In a transaction which produces gain is not complete until this is some enforceable right to gain, and that doesn’t occur here.","start":2198.556,"stop":2209.21,"duration":10.65}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But didn’t the Government on this case claim the gain, it was realized in fiscal year ’65?","start":2209.21,"stop":2216.274,"duration":7.06}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, we still have that in the event that this decision is affirmed, it will go back to the District Court and goes through that.","start":2216.274,"stop":2223.649,"duration":7.38}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Well --","start":2223.649,"stop":2224.924,"duration":1.28}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, I know --","start":2224.924,"stop":2225.274,"duration":0.35}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"But the thing consider it anyway.","start":2225.274,"stop":2227.168,"duration":1.89},{"text":"It’s saying that the gain act was actually realized in ‘65 --","start":2227.168,"stop":2229.943,"duration":2.78}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Right.","start":2229.943,"stop":2230.799,"duration":0.86}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"--better than ’66.","start":2230.799,"stop":2232.167,"duration":1.37}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"It is saying that the gain was realized in 65 --","start":2232.167,"stop":2234.221,"duration":2.05}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"As well as the 337 issue.","start":2234.221,"stop":2237.453,"duration":3.23}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"That’s right.","start":2237.453,"stop":2238.349,"duration":0.9}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"That is in the year of the fire.","start":2238.349,"stop":2240.036,"duration":1.69}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"That is in the year of the fire, and we have that -- we have that question as to business interruption insurance.","start":2240.036,"stop":2245.862,"duration":5.83}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"And what’s the difference?","start":2245.862,"stop":2246.82,"duration":0.96}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it is a question of the time of the accrual, is it not?","start":2246.82,"stop":2253.185,"duration":6.36},{"text":"And we litigated that question on the Government draft that I think in all fairness, it drafted because it did not want to cloud this rather narrow issue, but there has been a Tax court case since which is held the business interruption insurance to the time of the recovery of the insurance is the time that it is reported that I doesn’t relate back.","start":2253.185,"stop":2273.831,"duration":20.65}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Whereas the other cases that indicated what year that a gain that there should be realized, let us forget the liquidation.","start":2273.831,"stop":2285.114,"duration":11.28},{"text":"Well, let us take Lucas versus North Texas Lumber Company.","start":2285.114,"stop":2287.926,"duration":2.81},{"text":"You know that, that was an action of purchased timberland and it was --","start":2287.926,"stop":2293.71,"duration":5.78}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"How about in the fire case?","start":2293.71,"stop":2296.462,"duration":2.75},{"text":"You have some cases like that?","start":2296.462,"stop":2297.82,"duration":1.36}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"You know fire case and casualty loss.","start":2297.82,"stop":2300.622,"duration":2.8}]},{"speakerName":"Byron R. White","textObjs":[{"text":"Casualty loss, when the insurance proceeds are paid in the following taxable year, which year --","start":2300.622,"stop":2307.752,"duration":7.13}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"The nearest thing that I have but I cannot say it to you or I think it is the nearest thing, Justice White is Helvering versus Hamel which is cited somewhere either in the petition for writ of certiorari in our brief, and that was a foreclosure sale.","start":2307.752,"stop":2322.505,"duration":14.75},{"text":"And they said, this Court said that the sale was not reportable at the time of decree for foreclosure.","start":2322.505,"stop":2330.809,"duration":8.3},{"text":"But, in the following year when the sale actually took place, that was the decision of this Court as to an accrual basis taxpayer, and I think that situation is similarly --","start":2330.809,"stop":2340.756,"duration":9.95}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well you say, I take it -- you say I take it that if there have never been a liquidation here, then the proceeds have been paid exactly as they were paid here, that the company by good accounting practice and good tax accounting practice would have returned the gain in fiscal 66.","start":2340.756,"stop":2361.19,"duration":20.43}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, no question about that in my mind and I think this case that I have cited, I cannot cite you a higher case or casualty at hand.","start":2361.19,"stop":2368.759,"duration":7.57},{"text":"But I think this line of cases Lucas versus North Texas Lumber Company which is also cited somewhere in the briefs, Helvering versus Hamel, they all hold to this effect.","start":2368.759,"stop":2379.758,"duration":11},{"text":"That is at the time that an obligation arises even if it as to an accrual basis taxpayer that the gain is reported and not at the time of the incident whether it be a casualty or the exercise of an option, or a foreclosure sale on the petitioner’s file.","start":2379.758,"stop":2400.209,"duration":20.45}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"On the condemnation?","start":2400.209,"stop":2402.343,"duration":2.13}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, the condemnation occurs of course at the time of the taking, there is no question about that.","start":2402.343,"stop":2407.052,"duration":4.71},{"text":"The only difference is on the cases that the Government cites are under we talked about and discussed yesterday are in those statute.","start":2407.052,"stop":2413.288,"duration":6.24},{"text":"Those peculiar in the minority, I mean, fewer statutes, I’m sure.","start":2413.288,"stop":2417.987,"duration":4.7},{"text":"Let’s say, under particular statutes that at the time the declaration is filed, the Government has the right to possession --","start":2417.987,"stop":2425.021,"duration":7.03}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"And, that is the taking","start":2425.021,"stop":2426.446,"duration":1.42}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"That is the taking.","start":2426.446,"stop":2427.095,"duration":0.65}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Under those statutes.","start":2427.095,"stop":2427.861,"duration":0.77}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"But under a majority of statutes, that does not happen until the deposit is put up or until the decree is put up, and then that taking occurs.","start":2427.861,"stop":2437.073,"duration":9.21},{"text":"But when you compare an involuntary conversion in those cases, you see, it is not the casualty itself; it’s the creation of the right to the obligation that compares to the taking and this occurred in this case after the adoption of the plan of liquidation.","start":2437.073,"stop":2455.627,"duration":18.55},{"text":"Thank you.","start":2455.627,"stop":2456.553,"duration":0.93}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you gentlemen.","start":2456.553,"stop":2457.222,"duration":0.67},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":2457.222,"stop":2457.42,"duration":0.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Mr. Snyder but there must be some law in this fire business, the casualty business of the loss in one taxable year and payment the next.","start":2457.42,"stop":2466.832,"duration":9.41}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"I’m sure there is but I cannot cite you by name and report number of the case.","start":2466.832,"stop":2471.722,"duration":4.89},{"text":"We did -- this was involved in the District Court and we prevailed there, and it was not taken to the Court of Bills by the government.","start":2471.722,"stop":2481.253,"duration":9.53},{"text":"I think in all fairness for the reason that I just said to you, I don’t think they want to cloud up this issue.","start":2481.253,"stop":2486.64,"duration":5.39}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"But certainly, I take it as of here are now, you and the Government were at loggerheads on that issue.","start":2486.64,"stop":2492.938,"duration":6.3}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, as a matter of fact -- as a matter of fact, when the decision was handed down in the Court of Appeals in this case, and before we could file our petition, the Government filed a motion in the District Court to consider this very question.","start":2492.938,"stop":2509.637,"duration":16.7},{"text":"So, I say that if we lose here, we’re going back to the District Court to argue that question, I have no --","start":2509.637,"stop":2517.21,"duration":7.57}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"What question?","start":2517.21,"stop":2518.655,"duration":1.45}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"The question of when this --","start":2518.655,"stop":2519.853,"duration":1.2}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Whether the corporation must pay to 50 to 65, or 66.","start":2519.853,"stop":2523.793,"duration":3.94}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Yes, in which year, and I don’t have any doubts as to how it is going to come out, I think we’re going to prevail, but nevertheless, they haven’t given up on this question.","start":2523.793,"stop":2533.853,"duration":10.06}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, isn’t that irrelevant to this case, is it?","start":2533.853,"stop":2536.548,"duration":2.69},{"text":"To the --","start":2536.548,"stop":2537.125,"duration":0.58}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, it’s relevant --","start":2537.125,"stop":2538.72,"duration":1.59}]},{"speakerName":"UNKNOWN","textObjs":[{"text":"You don’t think it’s an important point or not with respect to the --","start":2538.72,"stop":2545.345,"duration":6.63}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"Time of accrual, the time of accrual, yes, I think it is but I think that the true concur in this case.","start":2545.345,"stop":2552.279,"duration":6.93},{"text":"I think that the involuntary conversion by casualty concurs with the accrual of the right to receive insurance proceeds.","start":2552.279,"stop":2565.541,"duration":13.26},{"text":"So, it’s important to that extent, yes.","start":2565.541,"stop":2568.493,"duration":2.95}]},{"speakerName":"William H. Rehnquist","textObjs":[{"text":"Well, did the judgment of the District Court that was handed down here purport to finally adjudicate all of the tax liability involved in your refund claim?","start":2568.493,"stop":2576.978,"duration":8.49}]},{"speakerName":"Larry H. Snyder","textObjs":[{"text":"I think that the Court’s body had but there is -- if I say again or repeat, if we lose here then we do have -- the Government has not abandoned that point.","start":2576.978,"stop":2589.788,"duration":12.81},{"text":"And of course, holding that these proceeds or entitle a man recognition, the Court -- the District Court was not presented then with the question of when are these proceeds report.","start":2589.788,"stop":2604.79,"duration":15},{"text":"So, it’s a -- as I say it hinges upon the decision of this Court as to whether that’s litigated.","start":2604.79,"stop":2611.361,"duration":6.57},{"text":"Thank you.","start":2611.361,"stop":2611.571,"duration":0.21}]},{"speakerName":"Warren E. Burger","textObjs":[{"text":"Thank you Mr. Snyder.","start":2611.571,"stop":2612.729,"duration":1.16},{"text":"Thank you Mr. Smith.","start":2612.729,"stop":2613.507,"duration":0.78},{"text":"The case is submitted.","start":2613.507,"stop":2615.093,"duration":1.59}]}]}],"decidedBy":"Burger Court","arguedOn":"Mar  25 - 26, 1974","petitioner":"Central Tablet Mfg. Company","respondent":"United States","docket":"73-593","citation":"417 US 673 (1974)","justiaLink":"https://supreme.justia.com/cases/federal/us/417/673","lowerCourt":"United States Court of Appeals for the Sixth Circuit","grantedOn":"","decidedOn":"Jun 19, 1974"}